note.p:
In both Dayʼs History of Sandford and Merton and Joyceʼs Scientific Dialogues,
                    the pupils are shown stars in the Plough or Wain that serve as “pointers” to the North Star or Polaris in the tail of the Bear,
                    enabling the boys to determine compass bearings in the dark. As Joyceʼs Tutor explains,
                    “if you wish to be a young astronomer”, a youth “must learn to find these [cardinal compass] points without the assistance of the sun”;
                    and he directs their eyes to “those seven stars which are in the constellation of the Great Bear”, which
                    “some people have supposed . . . aptly represent a plough;
                    others say, that they are more like a waggon and horses;—the four stars representing the body of the waggon, and the other three the horses”
                    (Joyce, Scientific Dialogues, vol. 2, “Of Astronomy”, conversation 2, “Of the Fixed Stars”, 15–16; 
                    see also Crux [the Southern Cross]).

Aspin adds a biblical type: “This fable is evidently founded upon the part acted by the serpent in the fall of our first parents; 
                        in consequence of which they and their posterity were excluded from the fruit of the tree of life, till One greater than Hercules should destroy him, 
                        and restore man to the primeval state of innocence and happiness” (A Familiar Treatise on Astronomy, 109).

“the northern crown“
              (RF T70; MS III)—Corona Borealis (the Northern Crown), northern constellation bounded by Boötes and Hercules; 
              included among the list of forty‐eight constellations by Ptolemy; 
              viewed from London, rises “immediately after Virgo, and may be seen in the evening from March to June” 
              (Aspin, A Familiar Treatise on Astronomy, 105, 123).

“the very fiery swan“
                    (RF T70; MS III)—Cygnus (the Swan), or Northern Cross; 
                    northern constellation, north of Vulpecula and Anser, bounded on east by Lacerta and Pegasus and on west by Lyra; ; included in the forty‐eight constellations listed by Ptolemy; 
                    “greater part of this constellation never set[s] to Britain” (Aspin, A Familiar Treatise on Astronomy, 105, 127).

“the little horse“
                    (RF T70; MS III)—Equüleus (Little Horse), northern constellation, 
                    south and west of Pegasus and east of Delphinus (the Dolphin); 
                    included in Ptolemyʼs list of forty‐eight constellations; 
                    in Britain, “visible in the evening from January to March. and from August to the close of the year” 
                    (Aspin, A Familiar Treatise on Astronomy, 105, 129–30).

“High up there is scorpio”
                    (MS IA; RF T70; 
                   MS III)—Scorpio (Scorpion), constellation of the southern Zodiac, 
                    the second southern and second autumn sign, eighth sign in the full order of the Zodiac, according to Jamieson,  
                   (Celestial Atlas, 45); 
                    between the zodiacal constellations of Sagittarius on its east and of Libra on its west, 
                   and bounded on its north by Ophiuchus and on its south by Lupus and Ara; 
                    “[r]ises in the S.E. and visible in the evening from June to August, but the tail never rises at London” 
                   (Aspin, A Familiar Treatise on Astronomy, 138).

“the generous leo“
                    (MS IA; RF T70; 
        MS III)—Leo (the Lion), 
        constellation of the northern Zodiac, 
                    the fifth in the order of the Zodiac and “second of the summer signs”, according to Jamieson 
                    (Celestial Atlas, 40); 
                    between the zodiacal constellations of Virgo on its east and of Cancer on its west, 
        and bounded on its north by Leo Minor, and on its south by Crater; 
                    in Britain, “rises in the E.N.E. and may be viewed in the evenings of January to May”, according to Aspin 
        (A Familiar Treatise on Astronomy, 106, 135).

“serpent serpent bearer then“
                    (MS IA; RF T70; 
                    MS III)—Serpens (Serpent) and Ophiuchus (Serpent Bearer) 
                    (the latter also known as Serpentarius), northern constellations; 
                    on the celestial equator, north of Scorpio and Libra; Serpens west of Ophiuchus, but the two constellations normally reckoned as one; 
                    in Britain, rise "E.N.E. and visible in the evening from May to December" 
                    (Aspin, A Familiar Treatise on Astronomy, 105, 224, 225).

“the very longbilled crane” 
                    (MS IA; RF T70; 
                    MS III)—Ruskin again turns to the southern hemisphere to name another of the twelve constellations observed by the Dutch explorers, 
                    Keyser and de Houtman. Grus (“no part of [which] is visible in our latitudes”, Jamieson remarks) 
                    is represented with a long beak and a long, bent neck, seen stretching in full flight, but only as a small figure in Jamiesonʼs plate 28 of the entire southern hemisphere; 
                    and it is named only, not shown in Greenʼs plate 15. It is drawn with its long neck and beak fully outstretched in Bodeʼs Uranographia (1801) 
                    (Jamieson, Celestial Atlas, 63; 
                    Astronomical Recreations, 93; 
                    Ridpath, Star Tales, 100).

“arched sky” 
                    (MS IA; RF T70; 
                    MS III)—A frequent poeticism found, e.g., in Sandysʼs translation of Ovid (1621–32):
